\aopssoln{Tintarn}{2}{https://aops.com/community/c7h2817872p24890588}

\begin{soln}
  First of all, it is clear that $x_n \in (0,1)$
  for all $n$ and hence $x_{n+1}<x_n$
  and hence $x_n$ converges and hence
  $\lim_{n \to \infty} x_n=0$.
  Next, by Stolz-Cesaro, using
  $\frac{1}{x_{n+1}}=\frac{1}{x_n}+\frac{1}{1-x_n}$, we have
  \[
    \lim_{n \to \infty} \frac{1}{nx_n}
    =\lim_{n \to \infty} \left(\frac{1}{x_{n+1}}
    -\frac{1}{x_n}\right)
    =\lim_{n \to \infty} \frac{1}{1-x_n}=1
  .\qedhere\]
\end{soln}
